{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01LMsdGf6Yc24yjJmhEvtuCG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) and UDP (User Datagram Protocol) are core transport-layer protocols with different tradeoffs.\n\n**TCP** is connection-oriented. Before data flows, endpoints perform a three-way handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK) to establish state. It guarantees reliable, ordered, byte-stream delivery: each segment carries a sequence number, the receiver sends ACKs, and lost or out-of-order segments are retransmitted and reassembled. TCP also implements flow control (sliding window, advertised by the receiver) and congestion control (slow start, congestion avoidance, fast retransmit) to avoid overwhelming the network or peer. The header is ~20 bytes minimum and includes sequence/ack numbers, window size, and flags. Used by HTTP/1.1, HTTPS, SSH, SMTP.\n\n**UDP** is connectionless and stateless. It just wraps a payload in an 8-byte header (source port, dest port, length, checksum) and fires it off as an independent datagram. No handshake, no ACKs, no retransmission, no ordering, no congestion control. Packets can be lost, duplicated, or reordered, and the application must handle that. The benefit is minimal latency and overhead, plus support for multicast/broadcast.\n\nUDP fits DNS, VoIP, gaming, video streaming, and QUIC (which rebuilds reliability in userspace). TCP fits anything needing integrity over speed."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9492,"cache_read_input_tokens":16191,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9492},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2DF79530-324B-43F3-92A3-D898DDEE7E6B","uuid":"9f6d62b3-5ffc-43f0-a883-fb3808301479"}
